    "body": "Since the amount passed to the `to_little_endian_64` function is in Gwei,  2^64 means ~18 billion (~ 10^10) Ether, which is greater than the current supply ~110 million Ether.   \r\n\r\nWe discussed this during audit/formal verification and let it pass due to the infeasibility in mainnet conditions.\r\n\r\nThere used to be a `assert deposit_amount <= MAX_DEPOSIT_AMOUNT` but this was removed in favor of allowing deposits higher than `MAX_DEPOSIT_AMOUNT` (32 ETH) as an acceptable input (the user can just top-up balance even if this bound was in place).\r\n\r\nFortunately, even in the case that the depositor does deposit `>= 2^64` ETH, `to_little_endian_64(deposit_amount)` will return (the little endian representation of)  `deposit_amount mod 2^64`.  So, the depositor will lose funds rather than minting funds.\r\n\r\nI'm not opposed to adding an `assert deposit_amount < 2^64` but also don't necessarily want to disturb the FV unless we open it up for other reasons.",
